        <button onClick={handleChanges}>Make Changes</button>
    );
}
In this example, the handleClick function in the parent component dispatches a custom event called 'saveEvent' which carries the handleSave function as its detail. This event is then picked up by the useEffect hook in the child component, which listens for this specific event, and when it sees it will invoke the handleSave with the changes.You also could use a state hook in the parent component to track if the save button was pressed, and use that information to call the handleSave in the child component. For example:Copy code// Parent component
function Parent() {
    const [isSaveClicked, setIsSaveClicked] = useState(false);

    const handleSave = (changes) => {
        console.log("Save changes:"+changes);
    };

    const handleClick = (e) => {
        setIsSaveClicked(true);
    };

    return (
        <div>
            <button onClick={handleClick}>Save</button>
            <EditMenu isSaveClicked={isSaveClicked} handleSave={handleSave} />
        </div>
    );
}

// Child component
function EditMenu({ isSaveClicked, handleSave }) {
    const handleChanges = () => {
        const changes = ["change1", "change2"];
        if (isSaveClicked) {
            handleSave(changes);
        }
    };

    return (
        <button onClick={handleChanges}>Make Changes</button>
    );
}
In this example, when the button in the parent component is clicked, it sets the isSaveClicked state variable to true. The child component receives this state variable as a prop, and when the button within the child component is clicked, it checks the value of isSaveClicked and if it's true, it calls the handleSave function and pass the changes, otherwise nothing will happen.What are the pros and cons of each approach?Here are some pros and cons of each approach:Using event listeners:Pros:It allows for decoupling the child and parent components, so that they don't need to be tightly coupled.The child component can be reused in other places, without changing the parent.Cons:You need to be careful when using global events, it can make the code harder to reason about and test.There's a chance of naming conflicts if other parts of the application are also using the same event names.Using state hooks and props:Pros:The approach is straightforward and easy to understand.It allows for simple and explicit communication between the child and parent components.Cons:The child component is tightly coupled to the parent component and it needs to have knowledge of the parent state, which can make the child component less reusable.The application could become less performant if you have a large number of props that are being passed around, because the component will re-render each time one of those props change.It is important to note that there's no one-size-fits-all answer, you should choose the approach that works best for your use-case and that makes the most sense for your application.
